One America, Two Kinds of Citizens
New York—As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting ballots from the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the results are finally confirmed, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This was to be expected in this fiercely contested, record-breaking election.
Only U.S. citizens can vote in the presidential election, but this choice affects people all across the country.
If it is too early to confirm the election results now, it is not too early to examine the implications of this election for the world's most powerful country.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a strong democratic nation.
Despite practical limitations related to the pandemic, voter turnout remained high.
This process seems to be unfolding as planned.
Moreover, violent incidents are rare.
Courts are investigating decisions by the U.S. Postal Service that appear to be politically motivated and hindered the delivery of ballots from regions where votes are expected to primarily come from the Democratic Party.
President Trump's unsubstantiated claim of victory on Tuesday evening received little response, and his demand to halt the counting of ballots (at least in the states where he was leading) seemed to be ignored.
However, it is concerning that the divide among U.S. voters remains significant.
The votes for the two candidates are almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a divided government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and maintain control of the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The seats for governors and state legislatures are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republican Party having a slight edge).
The anticipated "blue wave" for the Democratic Party did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a significant margin, securing around four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million cast.
But Republicans held onto many seats that were predicted to flip in the Senate, while the Democratic Party actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This result did not come from a strong mandate, nor did it stem from political maneuvering.
Trump's poll numbers were very strong, securing five million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter among all U.S. presidential candidates in history and surpassing any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily increases in both new COVID-19 cases and deaths, with over 100,000 new cases and more than 1,000 deaths reported each day.
Just as the consequences of his government's mishandling of the pandemic were becoming most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump lost, which seems likely, he will still wield significant influence, especially if he remains in the public eye, which also seems possible.
Even if he does not run himself, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican nominee in the next presidential election in 2024.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a modern form of American populism — will still remain a powerful force.
As expected, despite lacking any evidence, Trump has made every effort to portray himself as noble and upright, attempting to undermine the legitimacy of the election results and accusing others of fraud.
Many of his supporters will reject the legitimacy of Biden's presidency.
Trump is very likely to never concede and even less likely to attend the inauguration of his successor.
As the saying goes by Will Rogers, Trump has never met a rule he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They categorize themselves into different communities and regions based on shared viewpoints.
And each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
And the absence of a national civics curriculum has facilitated the differentiation among people of different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that the country's divisions are mostly not drawn along economic lines.
People from all social classes voted for the two candidates, and the voting patterns by demographics, gender, and race were not as one-sided as many had predicted.
Their differences mainly lie in the remedies.
Educational level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographic location. Republican voters tend to reside in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to reside in metropolitan areas.
However, culture may play a larger role in American politics than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy did not seem to be very important in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
In such a context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the presidential election process or the way government operates.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representation, but it is unlikely that a consensus on reform can be reached, because any potential solution would benefit some people while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who stand to lose from change will resist it.
This will make governance difficult.
This will largely depend on the assessment of Republican Senate leader Mitch McConnell, as well as his ability and willingness to cooperate with the incoming Biden administration.
Collaboration will also require compromises from Biden, which will certainly face resistance from ideologically strong members within his own party.
Democrats have attempted to sharply deny everything Trump represents and stands for.
But they were not successful.
While Republicans are seeking an election that would recognize Trump.
But this did not go as they wished.
On the contrary, the election revealed a nation and two types of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
